From 8dc518b814e002128da75da43273847673f046ba Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: tcfialho <tcfialho@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 19 Jun 2026 00:34:43 -0300
Subject: [PATCH 3/7] maindeck anim Step 1: close fade via compositor-owned
 orphan snapshot

A closing window is torn down within the next manage+render cycle after unmap
(far sooner than a 200ms fade), so a close animation cannot live on the Window.
Instead, at unmap we snapshot the window's live buffers into a standalone scene
tree owned by a new orphan subsystem (Animation.OrphanClose), arm a fade-out,
and advance it in the same output frame loop. The orphan self-destructs when the
fade completes; the window's protocol lifecycle finishes immediately and
independently (taskbar updates at once).

- buffers are copied (not reparented from SaveableSurfaces.saved_tree, whose
  dropSaved would destroy them mid-fade); scene buffers hold refs so the
  snapshot outlives the client surface.
- orphan list is walked in handleFrame alongside window anims; server deinit
  frees any in-flight orphans before the scene graph is torn down.
- scheduling consolidated into Animation.scheduleAllOutputFrames (removed the
  duplicate in Output).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
